Show that the linear transformation T is not surjective by finding an element of the codomain, \vect{v}, such that there is no vector \vect{u} with \lteval{T}{\vect{u}}=\vect{v}.\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{3}},\quad
                \lteval{T}{\colvector{a\\b\\c}}=
                \colvector{2a+3b-c\\2b-2c\\a-b+2c}

solution.p:
Now, show \rng{T}\subseteq\csp{A}.  Choose \vect{y}\in\rng{T}.  Then by , there is a vector \vect{x} in \complex{n} such that \lteval{T}{\vect{x}}=\vect{y}.  Then
                    A\vect{x}
                    &=\lteval{T}{\vect{x}}&&
                        \text{Definition of }T
                    &=\vect{y}
                .  So by  and , \vect{y} qualifies for membership in \csp{A} and so \rng{T}\subseteq\csp{A}.
